<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="502" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,1790,1959]" pageId="13" pageNumber="502">
The species is known from Central America (Belize). The host plant remains unknown. On the basis of our current re-examination, this species, previously with uncertain and provisional taxonomic position (see Puplesis &amp; Robinson 2000), is transferred from the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Braun" authorityName="Braun" authorityYear="1917" box="[676,887,1862,1887]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Glaucolepis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[676,811,1862,1887]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="502">Glaucolepis</emphasis>
Braun
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick" authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1921" box="[924,1142,1862,1887]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Acalyptris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[924,1039,1862,1887]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="502">Acalyptris</emphasis>
Meyrick
</taxonomicName>
(a description and figures of a re-examination of the male genitalia, wing venation and wing scaling, with formerly unnoticed but hardly visible and very specific androconia, will be presented by Stonis &amp; Remeikis, 
<emphasis box="[1027,1114,1935,1958]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="502">in prep.</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
